WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.884
Croup, or laryngotracheobronchitis, is a
common

2
00:00:03.884 --> 00:00:08.725
pediatric upper airway condition that
every respiratory therapist needs to recognize quickly.

3
00:00:09.524 --> 00:00:13.625
It's typically caused by a viral
infection, most often parainfluenza,

4
00:00:13.925 --> 00:00:17.684
and it leads to inflammation and swelling
in the larynx and trachea,

5
00:00:17.885 --> 00:00:19.784
especially in the subglottic region.

6
00:00:20.145 --> 00:00:24.704
Because children have naturally smaller
airways, even a small amount

7
00:00:24.704 --> 00:00:27.424
of swelling can significantly increase
airway resistance.

8
00:00:27.424 --> 00:00:31.504
This is why CRUPE presents with that
classic triad, a

9
00:00:31.504 --> 00:00:33.865
barking cough, hoarseness, and inspiratory
stridor.

10
00:00:34.584 --> 00:00:35.904
And that stridor is key.

11
00:00:36.345 --> 00:00:39.384
It tells you this is an upper airway
problem, not

12
00:00:39.384 --> 00:00:41.284
a lower airway issue like asthma.

13
00:00:41.645 --> 00:00:45.604
From an RT perspective, your priority is
not just identifying

14
00:00:45.605 --> 00:00:47.925
Croup, it's determining severity.

15
00:00:48.305 --> 00:00:52.485
A child with just a barking cough and no
stridor at rest is likely

16
00:00:53.244 --> 00:00:56.625
Once you hear stridor at rest, see
retractions,

17
00:00:56.705 --> 00:01:00.384
or notice agitation, you're dealing with
at least moderate disease.

18
00:01:01.005 --> 00:01:03.505
And if that child becomes fatigued,
hypoxic,

19
00:01:03.544 --> 00:01:07.065
or less responsive, that's a red flag for
impending respiratory

20
00:01:07.065 --> 00:01:07.404
failure.

21
00:01:08.165 --> 00:01:12.205
One of the most important concepts in
Croup management is minimizing agitation.

22
00:01:13.144 --> 00:01:17.345
Crying increases airflow demand and
worsens airway narrowing, so keeping

23
00:01:17.345 --> 00:01:19.025
the child calm is critical.

24
00:01:19.644 --> 00:01:22.764
Often, that means allowing them to stay
with a and

25
00:01:22.764 --> 00:01:24.864
avoiding unnecessary procedures.

26
00:01:25.764 --> 00:01:32.824
Treatment typically includes
corticosteroids like dexamethasone to reduce inflammation and nebulized epinephrine for moderate

27
00:01:32.824 --> 00:01:33.925
to severe cases.

28
00:01:34.625 --> 00:01:39.605
Epinephrine works quickly by causing
vasoconstriction, which temporarily reduces airway

29
00:01:39.605 --> 00:01:42.404
swelling, but remember its effects can
wear off.

30
00:01:42.785 --> 00:01:45.644
That's why monitoring after treatment is
essential.

31
00:01:45.925 --> 00:01:49.044
As an RT, you'll also support oxygenation,

32
00:01:49.504 --> 00:01:52.224
assess work of breathing, listen for
changes in air movement,

33
00:01:52.544 --> 00:01:54.205
and monitor for rebound symptoms.

34
00:01:54.845 --> 00:01:56.904
And always keep your differential in mind.

35
00:01:57.525 --> 00:01:59.985
Drooling, toxic appearance, or sudden
onset

36
00:02:00.025 --> 00:02:05.705
should make you think about more serious
conditions like epiglottitis or foreign body aspiration.

37
00:02:06.544 --> 00:02:10.145
Bottom line, Croup is an upper airway
emergency spectrum.

38
00:02:10.804 --> 00:02:14.264
Your job is to recognize where the patient
falls on that spectrum,

39
00:02:15.244 --> 00:02:18.384
intervene appropriately, and escalate
early if things worsen.

